[start section id="20112"]

#1 T2, N1c (TD), AJCC stage IIIA, Dukes stage C colorectal cancer, status-post extended low-anterior resection with J-pouch descending colorectostomy
#2 Chromophobe renal cell carcinoma, grade 2, stage T1a, status-post right partial nephrectomy
PLAN
At this time for his rectal carcinoma, he has already received neoadjuvant concurrent chemoradiation therapy with Xeloda.  The plan would be now to initiate FOLFOX 6 regimen which was discussed at length with him.  The plan would be to give a total of eight cycles with each cycle being 14 days.  He already has a port  in place.  I discussed at length the side-effects of therapy including but not limited to life-threatening infections, diarrhea, febrile neutropenia, myelosuppression, cardiac side-effects, dehydration, mucositis, acute and peripheral neuropathy related to FOLFOX regimen.  He understands that since none of these drugs have been tried before, it is possible he might be allergic to one of them.  He is willing to proceed.  We will administer as many cycles as possible before his surgical closure of ileostomy which is scheduled in January.  A month prior to the scheduled procedure, his cycles would have to be stopped and resumed a month after the procedure.  This approach has been recommended by Dr. Braaten, his primary colorectal surgeon.  I have discussed the case extensively with Dr. Kale who agrees with aforementioned approach at this time.
ADVANCE DIRECTIVES
Advance directive or living will: No, not interested in additional information.

